headline: UnitedHealth forecasts first revenue drop in nearly four decades
summary: STORY: Shares of UnitedHealth Group plunged as much as 20% Tuesday morning after the health insurer said revenue would decline this year for the first time since 1989.The forecast follows Monday's lower‑than‑expected 2027 Medicare reimbursement proposal from the U.S. government.Analysts said the prospect of lower government revenue from the Medicare plans for people aged 65 and older or with disabilities deepened worries about UnitedHealth's recovery.UnitedHealth missed earnings estimates last year for the first time since 2008.It dealt with a cyberattack that caused customer losses, unexpected increases in medical fees and use, and fallout from the murder of a top executive that set off a wave of criticism from Americans resentful of healthcare costs and service denials. The company last year fired CEO Andrew Witty and brought back former chief executive Steve Hemsley, who has promised a turnaround.Hemsley expressed optimism on the earnings call, saying quote, “Momentum inside this organization is palpable. We still have work to do over the next several months, but I’m very pleased with the performance and outlook we have.”Despite the projected revenue decline, UnitedHealth said it expected profit to grow and slightly top the current average forecast of analysts.
